re surprised to find out, is that disability attorneys and advocate groups, like the one John used, only get paid a small percentage of back disability payments after you win your approval. These payments are capped by law to 25% up to $6,000.00. This is one of the major reasons why advocacy groups are <em>extremely selective</em> in the cases they take on.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">If a person never receives approval for disability benefits, they don’t have to pay a dime. “For me I didn’t mind paying someone after I won approval if it meant peace of mind.”, John said. “It was like I could finally sleep at night knowing that there was a group fighting for me, making sure everything was done correctly”.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">Although disability advocacy groups cannot guarantee a quicker approval, they can reduce the time lost having to refile due to technical errors, which as mentioned above, is one of the major reasons for first time denials. “I’m happy with how everything turned out” said John. “If I was going through this process again, I would get on the phone with an advocacy group right away to see if they could help, it would have saved me months of unnecessary anxiety”.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">To learn more about advocacy groups like the one mentioned in this article, <a href=\"https://www.disability-benefits-help.org/cpc/about-ssdi?utm_source=google&amp;utm_medium=cpc&amp;utm_term=disability%20benefits&amp;utm_content=225101598144&amp;utm_campaign=SSD+-+Phrase+Always&amp;__egma[MatchType]=p&amp;__egma[Network]=g&amp;__egma[Device]=c&amp;__egma[Creative]=225101598144&amp;__egma[Placement]=&amp;__egma[AdPosition]=1t1&amp;gclid=EAIaIQobChMI-_2d2KaM1wIVF7jACh0fsQS1EAAYASAAEgId3_D_BwE\"><u>click here</u></a></p></div>'),(747,70,'tve_revision_tve_has_wistia_popover','0'),(752,71,'tve_revision_tve_landing_page',''),(753,71,'tve_revision_tve_content_before_more','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_heading\"><h1 data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\" style=\"text-align: left;\">DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A <em>Little Understood</em> Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved.</h1></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">October 27, 2017 Boston, MA:<br><br>Americans who become disabled and need to apply for Social Security Disability benefits are stunned when they learn how difficult the U.S. Government makes it for them to gain approval.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">John Sterling, a 56-year-old carpenter, became disabled in 2012. “When I got the news from my Doctor that I would not be able to work again, I was struck with a lot of anxiety” John recalls. “A lot of financial worries, but my first order of business was to apply for disability”.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">He, like many Americans did not plan to become disabled, it happened suddenly, a brain aneurysm that he had no control over. “When I heard the news that I would not be able to work again, I thought it would be easy to apply for and gain approval for disability benefits that I have been paying into my entire life”, he said. “Boy was I wrong, the application was hard to complete and I received a letter of denial citing lack of hard medical evidence”.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">This is not uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration shows that roughly 68% of first time applicants are initially denied. These denials are different case to case, but the most common reason is for failing to complete the application correctly and not supplying enough information.&nbsp;</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">Once a person is denied, they have 60 days to file an appeal. For people like John, this task can be overwhelming and personally deflating. He was puzzled, “I was crushed, how is it that I pay into a program for 25 years and then when I unfortunately need to use it, the Government is not there for me?”</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">&nbsp;It was time to try another option – A little understood resource that is available to every disabled American.That option, was reaching out to a disability advocacy firm to get some questions answered. “You should be able to just apply and get an approval from the Social Security Administration (SSA), but that’s just not the case. You can’t do it on your own anymore”.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">Current statistics from the SSA estimate that the average wait time for a hearing is 602 days or 1.6 years. For people like John, receiving a denial because the application was not completed correctly might have added months onto the wait time for approval.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">Every month of waiting drains even more from their savings account. “My bills were piling up and I could not sleep at night, constantly worrying about not being able to provide for my family, I did not want to screw up on the appeals” said John.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">He finally gave into the ads he was seeing online for the disability advocacy group, <strong><em>Disability Freedom</em></strong>. “What ran through my mind were fears that using an attorney would cost too much and they would drain me even more, I just could not afford it.”</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f549629d7\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">What many people are surprised to find out, is that disability attorneys and advocate groups, like the one John used, only get paid a small percentage of back disability payments after you win your approval. These payments are capped by law to 25% up to $6,000.00. This is one of the major reasons why advocacy groups are <em>extremely selective</em> in the cases they take on.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">If a person never receives approval for disability benefits, they don’t have to pay a dime. “For me I didn’t mind paying someone after I won approval if it meant peace of mind.”, John said. “It was like I could finally sleep at night knowing that there was a group fighting for me, making sure everything was done correctly”.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">Although disability advocacy groups cannot guarantee a quicker approval, they can reduce the time lost having to refile due to technical errors, which as mentioned above, is one of the major reasons for first time denials. “I’m happy with how everything turned out” said John. “If I was going through this process again, I would get on the phone with an advocacy group right away to see if they could help, it would have saved me months of unnecessary anxiety”.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">To learn more about advocacy groups like the one mentioned in this article, <a href=\"https://www.disability-benefits-help.org/cpc/about-ssdi?utm_source=google&amp;utm_medium=cpc&amp;utm_term=disability%20benefits&amp;utm_content=225101598144&amp;utm_campaign=SSD+-+Phrase+Always&amp;__egma[MatchType]=p&amp;__egma[Network]=g&amp;__egma[Device]=c&amp;__egma[Creative]=225101598144&amp;__egma[Placement]=&amp;__egma[AdPosition]=1t1&amp;gclid=EAIaIQobChMI-_2d2KaM1wIVF7jACh0fsQS1EAAYASAAEgId3_D_BwE\"><u>click here</u></a></p></div>'),(754,71,'tve_revision_tve_content_more_found',''),(755,71,'tve_revision_tve_save_post',''),(756,71,'tve_revision_tve_custom_css','@media (min-width: 300px){[data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\"] { line-height: 1.25em !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f549629d7\"] { padding-bottom: 0px !important; margin-top: 0px !important; padding-top: 0px !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\"] { font-size: 17px !important; font-family: Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }}'),(757,71,'tve_revision_tve_user_custom_css',''),(758,71,'tve_revision_tve_page_events','a:0:{}'),(759,71,'tve_revision_tve_globals','a:2:{s:1:\"e\";s:1:\"1\";s:8:\"font_cls\";a:0:{}}'),(760,71,'tve_revision_tve_global_scripts',''),(761,71,'tve_revision_thrive_icon_pack','0'),(762,71,'tve_revision_thrive_tcb_post_fonts','a:0:{}'),(763,71,'tve_revision_tve_has_masonry','0'),(764,71,'tve_revision_tve_has_typefocus','0'),(765,71,'tve_revision_tve_updated_post','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_heading\"><h1 data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\" style=\"text-align: left;\">DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A <em>Little Understood</em> Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved.</h1></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">October 27, 2017 Boston, MA:<br><br>Americans who become disabled and need to apply for Social Security Disability benefits are stunned when they learn how difficult the U.S. Government makes it for them to gain approval.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">John Sterling, a 56-year-old carpenter, became disable