</div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">Why Do Initial Applications Have A High Rate of Denial?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d8467\">The Social Security Administration might deny an applicant who has a valid case for several reasons:<br>• Missing or not enough medical documentation of condition in application<br>• Application was not completed correctly<br>• Applicant is working above Substantial Gainful Activity (SGA) levels earning more than $1,090 per month.<br>• Applicant is not seeking regular medical treatment with a doctor or medical expert<br>• Applicant’s disabling condition is curable in under a year</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Are The Fees If I Hire An Attorney?<em>​</em></h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d9dfd\">Federally regulated by the Social Security Administration itself and applies to all attorneys or disability advocates, the attorney receives one-fourth of the back due benefits or $6,000 whichever is less if the claimant wins. Should the claimant lose the case, there are no fees involved and the attorney or advocate incurs all costs.</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">How Long To Receive An Answer From Social Security?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736dba98\">The initial application process takes 30 to 90 days for the initial decision. If denied, an individual has 65 days to file a request for reconsideration and will take another 30 to 90 days to receive a decision from the SSA. The application processing time varies depending on your medical condition(s), documentation provided, and whether or not you were denied and would like to file an appeal.</p></div></div>\n</div>'),(3021,195,'tve_revision_tve_has_wistia_popover','0'),(3022,196,'tve_revision_tve_landing_page',''),(3023,196,'tve_revision_tve_content_before_more','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">How Do I Apply For Social Security Disability Benefits?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d232f\">You can apply for disability benefits through the Social Security Administration directly here: https://www.ssa.gov/disabilityssi/.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Are The Qualifications to be Eligible For Social Security Disability Insurance?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p>According to the Social Security Administration (SSA)</p><ul class=\"\"><li>they have a physical or mental condition that prevents them from engaging in any \"substantial gainful activity\" (\"SGA\"), and</li><li>the condition is expected to last at least 12 months or result in death, and</li><li data-css=\"tve-u-15f737d7257\">they are under the age of 65, and</li><li>generally, they have accumulated 20 social security credits in the last 10 years prior to the onset of disability (normally four credits per full or partial year); one additional credit is required for every year by which the worker\'s age exceeds 42.</li></ul></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4>How Does Someone Accumulate 20 Social Security Credits?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f73728336\">What this equates to is a person must have worked full time for 20 of the last 40 quarters. This translates to 5 of the last 10 years. This does not have to consecutive employment, for example: If you work full time for 3yrs, took 2 yrs off, then worked full time for one year, took 2 years off, then worked full time for another year, you would satisfy the requirements.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4>What Kind Medical Evidence Is Required?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p>Medical evidence is signs, symptoms and laboratory findings and is required to document the claim. Symptoms, such as pain, are considered but must be reasonably expected to come from a medically determinable impairment which the claimant is diagnosed to have. The decision is based on a sequential evaluation of medical evidence. The sequence for adults is:</p><dl><dd>1. Is the claimant performing a substantial gainful activity? If yes, deny. If no, continue to next sequence.<br>2. Is the claimant\'s impairment severe? If no, deny. If yes, continue to next sequence.<br>3. Does the impairment meet or equal the severity of impairments in the Listing of Impairments?<sup><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Security_Disability_Insurance#cite_note-10\"></a>&nbsp;</sup>If yes, allow the claim. If no, continue to next sequence.<br>4. Is the claimant able to perform past work? If yes, deny. If no continue to next sequence.<br>5. Is the claimant able to perform any work in the economy? If yes, deny. If no allow the claim.</dd></dl><p>Medical evidence that demonstrates the applicant\'s inability to work is required. The DDS or ALJ may also require the applicant to visit a third-party physician for medical documentation, often to supplement the evidence treating sources do not supply. The applicant may meet a SSA medical listing for their condition. If their condition does not meet the requirements of a listing, their residual functional capacity is considered, along with their age, past relevant work, and education, in determining their ability to perform either their past work, or other work generally available in the national economy.</p></div></div>\n</div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Are The Odds To Receive Approval?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d3d1a\">Data from the Social Security Administration tells us that 65% of first time applications are initially denied. At the hearing level, 54% of people are denied Nationally.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Do I Need To Apply For Disability Benefits?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d6c8d\">From the Social Security Administration, you need the following information: Birth and citizenship , marriage or divorce, children, U.S. Military Service, employer details, self employment details, banking information, medical condition references, medical conditions, treating doctors and specialists, medical records, job history, any education and training.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">Why Do Initial Applications Have A High Rate of Denial?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d8467\">The Social Security Administration might deny an applicant who has a valid case for several reasons:<br>• Missing or not enough medical documentation of condition in application<br>• Application was not completed correctly<br>• Applicant is working above Substantial Gainful Activity (SGA) levels earning more than $1,090 per month.<br>• Applicant is not seeking regular medical treatment with a doctor or medical expert<br>• Applicant’s disabling condition is curable in under a year</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Are The Fees If I Hire An Attorney?<em>​</em></h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d9dfd\">Federally regulated by the Social Security Administration itself and applies to all attorneys or disability advocates, the attorney receives one-fourth of the back due benefits or $6,000 whichever is less if the claimant wins. Should the claimant lose the case, there are no fees involved and the attorney or advocate incurs all costs.</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">How Long To Receive An Answer From Social Security?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736dba98\">The initial application process takes 30 to 90 days for the initial decision. If denied, an individual has 65 days to file a request for reconsideration and will take another 30 to 90 days to receive a decision from the SSA. The application processing time varies depending on your medical condition(s), documentation provided, and whether or not you were denied and would like to file an appeal.</p></div></div>\n</div>'),(3024,196,'tve_revision_tve_content_more_found',''),(3025,196,'tve_revision_tve_save_post',''),(3026,196,'tve_revision_tve_custom_css','@media (min-width: 300px){[data-css=\"tve-u-15f737d7257\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f737d7257\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f73728336\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f73728336\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f736dba98\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f736dba98\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d9dfd\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d9dfd\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d8467\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d8467\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d6c8d\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d6c8d\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d3d1a\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d3d1a\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d232f\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d232f\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }}'),(3027,196,'tve_revision_tve_user_custom_css',''),(3028,196,'tve_revision_tve_page_events','a:0:{}'),(3029,196,'tve_revision_tve_globals','a:2:{s:1:\"e\";s:1:\"1\";s:8:\"font_cls\";a:0:{}}'),(3030,196,'tve_revision_tve_global_scripts',''),(3031,196,'tve_revision_thrive_icon_pack','0'),(3032,196,'tve_revision_thrive_tcb_post_fonts','a:0:{}'),(3033,196,'tve_revision_tve_has_masonry','0'),(3034,196,'tve_revision_tve_has_typefocus','0'),(3035,196,'tve_revision_tve_updated_post','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">How Do I Apply For Social Security Disability Benefits?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d232f\">You can apply for disability benefits through the Social Security Administration directly here: https://www.ssa.gov/disabilityssi/.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Are The Qualifications to be Eligible For Social Security Disability Insurance?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p>According to the Social Security Administration (SSA)</p><ul class=\"\"><li>they have a physical or mental condition that prevents them from engaging in any \"substantial gainful activity\" (\"SGA\"), and</li><li>the condition is expected to last at least 12 months or result in death, and</li><li data-css=\"tve-u-15f737d7257\">they are under the age of 65, and</li><li>generally, they have accumulated 20 social security credits in the last 10 years prior to the onset of disability (normally four credits per full or partial year); one additional credit is required for every year by which the worker\'s age exceeds 42.</li></ul></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4>How Does Someone Accumulate 20 Social Security Credits?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f73728336\">What this equates to is a person must have worked full time for 20 of the last 40 quarters. This translates to 5 of the last 10 years. This does not have to consecutive employment, for example: If you work full time for 3yrs, took 2 yrs off, then worked full time for one year, took 2 years off, then worked full time for another year, you would satisfy the requirements.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4>What Kind Medical Evidence Is Required?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p>Medical evidence is signs, symptoms and laboratory findings and is required to document the claim. Symptoms, such as pain, are considered but must be reasonably expected to come from a medically determinable impairment which the claimant is diagnosed to have. The decision is based on a sequential evaluation of medical evidence. The sequence for adults is:</p><dl><dd>1. Is the claimant performing a substantial gainful activity? If yes, deny. If no, continue to next sequence.<br>2. Is the claimant\'s impairment severe? If no, deny. If yes, continue to next sequence.<br>3. Does the impairment meet or equal the severity of impairments in the Listing of Impairments?<sup><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Social_Security_Disability_Insurance#cite_note-10\"></a>&nbsp;</sup>If yes, allow the claim. If no, continue to next sequence.<br>4. Is the claimant able to perform past work? If yes, deny. If no continue to next sequence.<br>5. Is the claimant able to perform any work in the economy? If yes, deny. If no allow the claim.</dd></dl><p>Medical evidence that demonstrates the applicant\'s inability to work is required. The DDS or ALJ may also require the applicant to visit a third-party physician for medical documentation, often to supplement the evidence treating sources do not supply. The applicant may meet a SSA medical listing for their condition. If their condition does not meet the requirements of a listing, their residual functional capacity is considered, along with their age, past relevant work, and education, in determining their ability to perform either their past work, or other work generally available in the national economy.</p></div></div>\n</div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Are The Odds To Receive Approval?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d3d1a\">Data from the Social Security Administration tells us that 65% of first time applications are initially denied. At the hearing level, 54% of people are denied Nationally.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Do I Need To Apply For Disability Benefits?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d6c8d\">From the Social Security Administration, you need the following information: Birth and citizenship , marriage or divorce, children, U.S. Military Service, employer details, self employment details, banking information, medical condition references, medical conditions, treating doctors and specialists, medical records, job history, any education and training.&nbsp;</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">Why Do Initial Applications Have A High Rate of Denial?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d8467\">The Social Security Administration might deny an applicant who has a valid case for several reasons:<br>• Missing or not enough medical documentation of condition in application<br>• Application was not completed correctly<br>• Applicant is working above Substantial Gainful Activity (SGA) levels earning more than $1,090 per month.<br>• Applicant is not seeking regular medical treatment with a doctor or medical expert<br>• Applicant’s disabling condition is curable in under a year</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">What Are The Fees If I Hire An Attorney?<em>​</em></h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736d9dfd\">Federally regulated by the Social Security Administration itself and applies to all attorneys or disability advocates, the attorney receives one-fourth of the back due benefits or $6,000 whichever is less if the claimant wins. Should the claimant lose the case, there are no fees involved and the attorney or advocate incurs all costs.</p></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_contentbox_shortcode thrv-content-box\">\n<div class=\"tve-content-box-background\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-cb tve_empty_dropzone\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><h4 class=\"\">How Long To Receive An Answer From Social Security?</h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f736dba98\">The initial application process takes 30 to 90 days for the initial decision. If denied, an individual has 65 days to file a request for reconsideration and will take another 30 to 90 days to receive a decision from the SSA. The application processing time varies depending on your medical condition(s), documentation provided, and whether or not you were denied and would like to file an appeal.</p></div></div>\n</div>'),(3036,196,'tve_revision_tve_has_wistia_popover','0'),(3113,198,'tve_revision_tve_landing_page',''),(3114,198,'tve_revision_tve_content_before_more','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\"><strong>Time Required:</strong> 2 Minutes<br><br>“You never think it will happen to you – and then it does.”John Sterling is recalling his reaction when he received the news that he would never return to work.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">&nbsp;But Sterling wasn’t laid off – he was one of 375,000 Americans every year who are retired by their doctors for disabilities. He, like many Americans, never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change his life.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of Sterling’s wages have been paid into the Disability Insurance Trust Fund since the program was begun in 1956. “I thought it would be easy to apply for disability benefits, because I’ve been contributing my whole life,” Sterling said, trying to hide a grimace.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“Boy, was I wrong.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">He said he struggled with the application, and after he submitted it and was awaiting good news, he received a letter of denial in the mail citing a lack of hard medical evidence in his case.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“My doctor told me I was unable to go back to my job,” Sterling said. “He’s my doctor. What more medical evidence do they need?”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Unfortunately, John Sterling’s situation is far from uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration (SSA) shows that roughly 68 percent of first-time disability applicants are initially denied.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">While differing from case to case, the reasons for these denials commonly involve incorrect or incomplete applications with a lack of information. Given just 60 days to apply for an appeal, Sterling said he felt crushed and overwhelmed.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">&nbsp;“I’m a responsible citizen. I couldn’t understand why the government wasn’t willing to help me.” </p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e6b1606\"><h4 class=\"\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><strong>“I’m a responsible citizen. I couldn’t understand why the government wasn’t willing to help me.”</strong></em></h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Current data from the SSA estimates wait times for appeal hearings to take over 600 days, or nearly 20 months.&nbsp;</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Every month of waiting was another month that Sterling was pulling from his life’s reserves to cover daily expenses, slowly draining his savings account. “I wasn’t sleeping, I was constantly worrying,” Sterling said.&nbsp;</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“I was the breadwinner, and I needed to be able to provide for my family. It killed me that I wasn’t able to do that.”In need of another option, Sterling turned online for legal advice. “A friend recommended I look for an advocacy group, but that sounded expensive. I already couldn’t afford my bills,” he said. “I certainly didn’t think I could afford help.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">But online, he learned that disability attorneys and advocate groups such as Disability United are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">These payments are capped at 25 percent and limited to $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they take cases that they expect to win. If their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">And though disability advocacy does not guarantee a faster approval process, professional groups like these can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Sterling said he didn’t mind paying after the approval for the immense peace of mind he gained. “Knowing that I had a group of experts fighting for my case meant that I could finally sleep at night.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">I gave myself the best chance of a good outcome.”The best outcome was what Sterling, and the many other disability applicants every year who seek out help, received. Advocacy groups and disability attorneys build sophisticated cases for their clients to ensure that applications make it through all the hoops, and in today’s complex system, it truly takes an expert.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“You can’t do it on your own these days,” Sterling said. “My advocacy group gave me so much help and reassurance. I could have saved myself months of unnecessary anxiety if I had just known that sooner.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">If you want to learn more about advocacy groups like Disability United to see if they can help you or a loved one, click here.</p></div>'),(3115,198,'tve_revision_tve_content_more_found',''),(3116,198,'tve_revision_tve_save_post',''),(3117,198,'tve_revision_tve_custom_css','@media (min-width: 300px){[data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e6b1606\"] { margin-top: 0px !important; padding-top: 0px !important; margin-bottom: 30px !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }}'),(3118,198,'tve_revision_tve_user_custom_css',''),(3119,198,'tve_revision_tve_page_events','a:0:{}'),(3120,198,'tve_revision_tve_globals','a:2:{s:1:\"e\";s:1:\"1\";s:8:\"font_cls\";a:0:{}}'),(3121,198,'tve_revision_tve_global_scripts',''),(3122,198,'tve_revision_thrive_icon_pack','0'),(3123,198,'tve_revision_thrive_tcb_post_fonts','a:0:{}'),(3124,198,'tve_revision_tve_has_masonry','0'),(3125,198,'tve_revision_tve_has_typefocus','0'),(3126,198,'tve_revision_tve_updated_post','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\"><strong>Time Required:</strong> 2 Minutes<br><br>“You never think it will happen to you – and then it does.”John Sterling is recalling his reaction when he received the news that he would never return to work.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">&nbsp;But Sterling wasn’t laid off – he was one of 375,000 Americans every year who are retired by their doctors for disabilities. He, like many Americans, never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change his life.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of Sterling’s wages have been paid into the Disability Insurance Trust Fund since the program was begun in 1956. “I thought it would be easy to apply for disability benefits, because I’ve been contributing my whole life,” Sterling said, trying to hide a grimace.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“Boy, was I wrong.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">He said he struggled with the application, and after he submitted it and was awaiting good news, he received a letter of denial in the mail citing a lack of hard medical evidence in his case.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“My doctor told me I was unable to go back to my job,” Sterling said. “He’s my doctor. What more medical evidence do they need?”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Unfortunately, John Sterling’s situation is far from uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration (SSA) shows that roughly 68 percent of first-time disability applicants are initially denied.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">While differing from case to case, the reasons for these denials commonly involve incorrect or incomplete applications with a lack of information. Given just 60 days to apply for an appeal, Sterling said he felt crushed and overwhelmed.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">&nbsp;“I’m a responsible citizen. I couldn’t understand why the government wasn’t willing to help me.” </p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e6b1606\"><h4 class=\"\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><strong>“I’m a responsible citizen. I couldn’t understand why the government wasn’t willing to help me.”</strong></em></h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Current data from the SSA estimates wait times for appeal hearings to take over 600 days, or nearly 20 months.&nbsp;</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Every month of waiting was another month that Sterling was pulling from his life’s reserves to cover daily expenses, slowly draining his savings account. “I wasn’t sleeping, I was constantly worrying,” Sterling said.&nbsp;</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“I was the breadwinner, and I needed to be able to provide for my family. It killed me that I wasn’t able to do that.”In need of another option, Sterling turned online for legal advice. “A friend recommended I look for an advocacy group, but that sounded expensive. I already couldn’t afford my bills,” he said. “I certainly didn’t think I could afford help.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">But online, he learned that disability attorneys and advocate groups such as Disability United are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">These payments are capped at 25 percent and limited to $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they take cases that they expect to win. If their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">And though disability advocacy does not guarantee a faster approval process, professional groups like these can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Sterling said he didn’t mind paying after the approval for the immense peace of mind he gained. “Knowing that I had a group of experts fighting for my case meant that I could finally sleep at night.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">I gave myself the best chance of a good outcome.”The best outcome was what Sterling, and the many other disability applicants every year who seek out help, received. Advocacy groups and disability attorneys build sophisticated cases for their clients to ensure that applications make it through all the hoops, and in today’s complex system, it truly takes an expert.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“You can’t do it on your own these days,” Sterling said. “My advocacy group gave me so much help and reassurance. I could have saved myself months of unnecessary anxiety if I had just known that sooner.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">If you want to learn more about advocacy groups like Disability United to see if they can help you or a loved one, click here.</p></div>'),(3127,198,'tve_revision_tve_has_wistia_popover','0'),(3130,77,'_wp_old_slug','denied-how-thousands-of-suddenly-disabled-americans-are-getting-their-disability-benefits-approved-quicker'),(3152,199,'tve_revision_tve_landing_page',''),(3153,199,'tve_revision_tve_content_before_more','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\"><strong>Time Required:</strong> 2 Minutes<br><br>“You never think it will happen to you – and then it does.”John Sterling is recalling his reaction when he received the news that he would never return to work.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">&nbsp;But Sterling wasn’t laid off – he was one of 375,000 Americans every year who are retired by their doctors for disabilities. He, like many Americans, never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change his life.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of Sterling’s wages have been paid into the Disability Insurance Trust Fund since the program was begun in 1956. “I thought it would be easy to apply for disability benefits, because I’ve been contributing my whole life,” Sterling said, trying to hide a grimace.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“Boy, was I wrong.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">He said he struggled with the application, and after he submitted it and was awaiting good news, he received a letter of denial in the mail citing a lack of hard medical evidence in his case.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“My doctor told me I was unable to go back to my job,” Sterling said. “He’s my doctor. What more medical evidence do they need?”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Unfortunately, John Sterling’s situation is far from uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration (SSA) shows that roughly 68 percent of first-time disability applicants are initially denied.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">While differing from case to case, the reasons for these denials commonly involve incorrect or incomplete applications with a lack of information. Given just 60 days to apply for an appeal, Sterling said he felt crushed and overwhelmed.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">&nbsp;“I’m a responsible citizen. I couldn’t understand why the government wasn’t willing to help me.” </p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e6b1606\"><h4 class=\"\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><em><strong>“I’m a responsible citizen. I couldn’t understand why the government wasn’t willing to help me.”</strong></em></h4></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c6a5d7\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Current data from the SSA estimates wait times for appeal hearings to take over 600 days, or nearly 20 months.&nbsp;</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Every month of waiting was another month that Sterling was pulling from his life’s reserves to cover daily expenses, slowly draining his savings account. “I wasn’t sleeping, I was constantly worrying,” Sterling said.&nbsp;</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“I was the breadwinner, and I needed to be able to provide for my family. It killed me that I wasn’t able to do that.”In need of another option, Sterling turned online for legal advice. “A friend recommended I look for an advocacy group, but that sounded expensive. I already couldn’t afford my bills,” he said. “I certainly didn’t think I could afford help.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">But online, he learned that disability attorneys and advocate groups such as Disability United are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">These payments are capped at 25 percent and limited to $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they take cases that they expect to win. If their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">And though disability advocacy does not guarantee a faster approval process, professional groups like these can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">Sterling said he didn’t mind paying after the approval for the immense peace of mind he gained. “Knowing that I had a group of experts fighting for my case meant that I could finally sleep at night.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">I gave myself the best chance of a good outcome.”The best outcome was what Sterling, and the many other disability applicants every year who seek out help, received. Advocacy groups and disability attorneys build sophisticated cases for their clients to ensure that applications make it through all the hoops, and in today’s complex system, it truly takes an expert.</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">“You can’t do it on your own these days,” Sterling said. “My advocacy group gave me so much help and reassurance. I could have saved myself months of unnecessary anxiety if I had just known that sooner.”</p><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\">If you want to learn more about advocacy groups like Disability United to see if they can help you or a loved one, click here.</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv-page-section\">\n<div class=\"tve-page-section-out\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2f915\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-page-section-in tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2a4e4\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c67d17\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c64b30\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><u>Advertiser Disclosure:&nbsp;&nbsp;</u>SSDInsider is a consumer information site that offers free articles and information relating to Social Security Disability. Many of the companies whose services we mention provide us compensation when someone who clicks from our site becomes their customer. This is how we make money to support our site. Compensation may impact which companies we write about and which articles those companies appear. We do not mention all companies that provide a given service All opinions expressed on this site are our own.</p></div></div>\n</div>'),(3154,199,'tve_revision_tve_content_more_found',''),(3155,199,'tve_revision_tve_save_post',''),(3156,199,'tve_revision_tve_custom_css','@media (min-width: 300px){[data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c6a5d7\"] { margin-bottom: 65px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c67d17\"] { margin-top: 58px !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c64b30\"] { font-size: 13px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2f915\"] { background-color: rgb(89, 85, 85) !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2a4e4\"] p, #tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2a4e4\"] li, #tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2a4e4\"] blockquote, #tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2a4e4\"] address { color: rgb(252, 251, 251); }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e6b1606\"] { margin-top: 0px !important; padding-top: 0px !important; margin-bottom: 30px !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\"] { font-size: 17px !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f6e66d4d2\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }}'),(3157,199,'tve_revision_tve_user_custom_css','