rc=\"//ssdinsider.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/10/07WEALTH-01-master768-v2.jpg\"></span></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f82bcbe16\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f78172ae7\"><strong>Read Time: 2 Minutes</strong><br><em>Disability Insider</em><br>October 29, 2017<br><br>“You never think it will happen to you – and then it does.”John Sterling is recalling his reaction when he received the news that he would never return to work.<br><br>But Sterling wasn’t laid off – he was one of 375,000 Americans every year who are retired by their doctors for disabilities. He, like many Americans, never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change his life.<br><br>The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of Sterling’s wages have been paid into the Disability Insurance Trust Fund, a Government program that began in 1956. “I thought it would be easy to apply for disability benefits, because I’ve been contributing my whole life,” Sterling said, trying to hide a grimace.&nbsp; “Boy, was I wrong.”<br><br>He said he struggled with the application, and after he submitted it and was awaiting good news, he received a letter of denial in the mail citing a lack of hard medical evidence in his case.<br><br>“My doctor told me I was unable to go back to my job,” Sterling said. “He’s my doctor. What more medical evidence do they need?”<br><br>Unfortunately, John Sterling’s situation is far from uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration (SSA) shows that roughly 68 percent of first-time disability applicants are initially denied.<br><br>While differing from case to case, the reasons for these denials commonly involve incorrect or incomplete applications with a lack of information. Given just 60 days to apply for an appeal, Sterling said he felt crushed and overwhelmed. <br><br>“I’m a responsible citizen. I couldn’t understand why the government was trying to screw me.\"<br><br>Current data from the SSA estimates wait times for appeal hearings to take over 600 days, or nearly 20 months. <br><br>Every month of waiting was another month that Sterling was pulling from his life’s reserves to cover daily expenses, slowly draining his savings account. “I wasn’t sleeping, I was constantly worrying,” Sterling said. <br><br>“I was the breadwinner, and I needed to be able to provide for my family. It killed me that I wasn’t able to do that.”In need of another option, Sterling turned online for legal advice. “A friend recommended I look for an advocacy group, but that sounded expensive. I already couldn’t afford my bills,” he said. “I certainly didn’t think I could afford help.” <br><br>But online, he learned that disability attorneys and advocate groups such as the <a href=\"http://ssclaimadvocates.com/\"><u><strong><em>Social Security Claim Advocates</em></strong></u></a> are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved.<br><br>These payments are capped at 25 percent and limited to $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they take cases that they expect to win. If their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.<br><br>And though disability advocacy does not guarantee a faster approval process, professional groups like these can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome.<br><br>Sterling said he didn’t mind paying after the approval for the immense peace of mind he gained. “Knowing that I had a group of experts fighting for my case meant that I could finally sleep at night.<br><br>I gave myself the best chance of a good outcome.” The best outcome was what Sterling, and the many other disability applicants every year who seek out help, received. <br><br>Advocacy groups and disability attorneys build sophisticated cases for their clients to ensure that applications make it through all the hoops, and in today’s complex system, it truly takes an expert.<br><br>“You can’t do it on your own these days,” Sterling said. “My advocacy group gave me so much help and reassurance. I could have saved myself months of unnecessary anxiety if I had just known that sooner.”</p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv-page-section tcb-window-width\" style=\"width: 900px; left: -120px;\">\n<div class=\"tve-page-section-out\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73d77486\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-page-section-in tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f82cb7092\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_heading\"><h1 data-css=\"tve-u-15f7e1d9409\" style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;<em>Social Security Claim Advocates&nbsp;</em>does not accept everyone, you must qualify. If you\'re tired of waiting, then get help from the leaders in disability approval today:<a href=\"http://ssclaimadvocates.com\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f82cc5c11\"></a></h1></div></div>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv-button\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f82cf36d6\">\n<a href=\"http://ssclaimadvocates.com/\" class=\"tcb-button-link\" onclick=\"ga(\'send\',\'event\',\'clicks\',\'SSClaim_Advocates_Button_Click\',\'SSDI_Leads\');return\" true;\"\"=\"\">\n<span class=\"tcb-button-texts\"><span class=\"tcb-button-text thrv-inline-text\"><u>Click To Qualify</u></span></span>\n</a>\n</div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p><span data-css=\"tve-u-15f82c9ed24\" style=\"font-size: 20px;\">Or call them directly to have your questions answered even faster:</span>\n<a data-css=\"tve-u-15f82c9bfce\" href=\"tel:8554820729\">1-855-482-0729</a></p></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv-page-section\">\n<div class=\"tve-page-section-out\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2f915\"></div>\n<div class=\"tve-page-section-in tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c2a4e4\"><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\" data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c67d17\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f73c64b30\" style=\"text-align: center;\"><u>Advertiser Disclosure:&nbsp;&nbsp;</u>SSDInsider is a consumer information site that offers free articles and information relating to Social Security Disability. Many of the companies whose services we mention provide us compensation when someone who clicks from our site becomes their customer. This is how we make money to support our site. Compensation may impact which companies we write about and which articles those companies appear. We do not mention all companies that provide a given service All opinions expressed on this site are our own.</p></div></div>\n</div>'),(4444,287,'tve_revision_tve_has_wistia_popover','0'),(4454,289,'tve_revision_tve_landing_page',''),(4455,289,'tve_revision_tve_content_before_more','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_heading\"><h1 data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\" style=\"text-align: left;\">The Best Decision I Made to Get Disability Benefits Approved...</h1></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">By John Sterling<br>Boston,MA<br><br>I thought it would never happen to me. Stunned by the words of my Doctor when he told me I would never be able to work again. At first I didn’t know how to take the news, I was only 52 years old, but quickly I became angry, anxious, and overwhelmed with racing thoughts. <br><br>How many of you reading this right now experienced the same emotions when you received the news? <br><br>I bet every one of you. <br><br>At first I felt alone and ashamed, then angry at life. Why did this happen to me? how am I going to make ends meet? What are my kids going to think about me as a parent? Or my wife, knowing she has to be the breadwinner? <br><br>I was draining my life savings and frequently chose to provide my family with food over paying my bills.<br><br>Then the debt collectors started to call, <strong><em>I NEEDED an income because my wife could not handle it all herself</em></strong>. <br><br>Through research, I learned that 375,000 Americans every year are retired by their doctors for disabilities. <br><br>I never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change my life. <br><br>The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of my wages have been paid into the Disability Insurance Trust Fund since I began working full time.<br><br>But you would think that a program you have been paying into your entire life would be easy to access in the event that you needed its resources, right? <br><br>Not…<br><br>Applying for Social Security Disability Insurance was one of the most <strong><em>mentally exhausting</em></strong> things I have ever had to do. <br><br>After the I submitted the daunting application, I kept wondering to myself, <strong>“how long will this take to be approved”</strong>, but no one at the SSA could answer this question for me. I was constantly told, “you will receive a letter in the mail after they review your application”<br><br>It took a while from what I remember, but I was denied (Like most first time applicants) and became extremely anxious when I learned that I only had 60 days to file my appeal. <br><br>I asked around in forums and searched the web for advice, but the most common advice I found was to “lawyer up” and put them in the driver’s seat. <br><br>…but that sounded expensive. <br><br>I already couldn’t afford my bills and I certainly didn’t think I could afford to pay for help.<br><br>But online, I read that disability attorneys and advocate groups are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved. <br><br>The attorney fees are capped at 25 percent and limited to a maximum of $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they only take on cases that they expect to win. <br><br>If they take a case and their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.<br><strong><br>This sounded too good to be true…</strong><br><br>And when researching advocacy groups that could help I found out that some shysters will charge you out of pocket for things like making copies of paperwork or postage for mailing documents.<br><br>I did know in my heart that hiring an attorney or advocacy group was the right move for me and my family. I just had to find one that didn\'t charge out of pocket fees as well...&nbsp;<br><br>I couldn’t afford to be stressed out and angry all the time at the SSA. <br><br>I needed to be there emotionally for my family. <br><br>I interviewed over 5 potential groups that I thought could help me and inquired about their success rates and if they charge any out of pocket fees. <br><br>I ended up using a service called the SS Claim Advocates, which was one of the best decisions I have made during this stressful process. <br><br>Even though I had to pay them a percentage of my back pay that was owed to me, I felt that they handled all of the headaches that I read about online and I was not charged any out of pocket fees. <br><br>There are a few other great options for advocacy groups out there that provide a similar service so <strong><em>I encourage you to do some research</em></strong>. <br><br>Although advocacy groups like <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">SS Claim Advocates</a> cannot guarantee a faster approval, they can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome. <br><br>I finally received approval 22 months after my initial application and my advice to those who are in a similar situation would be to research a reputable advocacy group and make sure to always ask if they charge any out of pocket expenses, because they might not mention that up front. <br><br>You are going to wait whether you go through it yourself or have an expert handle it for you, why not sleep in peace knowing someone is fighting for you and your family?<br><br>Or…<br><br>you can use the same service I used, click the link: <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">www.SSClaimAdvocates.com</a>. It’s pretty simple, just enter your information and describe your condition. <br><br>Someone will review your case and get back to you to discuss your options...whatever they may be.&nbsp;<br><br>Either way, I thought I would offer some consolation to those frustrated by the process. <br><br>Don’t waste your energy stressing over this process, do what my friend said and “lawyer up”, put them in the driver’s seat so you can be there for your family.</p></div>'),(4456,289,'tve_revision_tve_content_more_found',''),(4457,289,'tve_revision_tve_save_post',''),(4458,289,'tve_revision_tve_custom_css','@media (min-width: 300px){[data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\"] { line-height: 1.25em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\"] { font-size: 17px !important; font-family: Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }}'),(4459,289,'tve_revision_tve_user_custom_css',''),(4460,289,'tve_revision_tve_page_events','a:0:{}'),(4461,289,'tve_revision_tve_globals','a:2:{s:1:\"e\";s:1:\"1\";s:8:\"font_cls\";a:0:{}}'),(4462,289,'tve_revision_tve_global_scripts',''),(4463,289,'tve_revision_thrive_icon_pack','0'),(4464,289,'tve_revision_thrive_tcb_post_fonts','a:0:{}'),(4465,289,'tve_revision_tve_has_masonry','0'),(4466,289,'tve_revision_tve_has_typefocus','0'),(4467,289,'tve_revision_tve_updated_post','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_heading\"><h1 data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\" style=\"text-align: left;\">The Best Decision I Made to Get Disability Benefits Approved...</h1></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">By John Sterling<br>Boston,MA<br><br>I thought it would never happen to me. Stunned by the words of my Doctor when he told me I would never be able to work again. At first I didn’t know how to take the news, I was only 52 years old, but quickly I became angry, anxious, and overwhelmed with racing thoughts. <br><br>How many of you reading this right now experienced the same emotions when you received the news? <br><br>I bet every one of you. <br><br>At first I felt alone and ashamed, then angry at life. Why did this happen to me? how am I going to make ends meet? What are my kids going to think about me as a parent? Or my wife, knowing she has to be the breadwinner? <br><br>I was draining my life savings and frequently chose to provide my family with food over paying my bills.<br><br>Then the debt collectors started to call, <strong><em>I NEEDED an income because my wife could not handle it all herself</em></strong>. <br><br>Through research, I learned that 375,000 Americans every year are retired by their doctors for disabilities. <br><br>I never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change my life. <br><br>The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of my wages have been paid into the Disability Insurance Trust Fund since I began working full time.<br><br>But you would think that a program you have been paying into your entire life would be easy to access in the event that you needed its resources, right? <br><br>Not…<br><br>Applying for Social Security Disability Insurance was one of the most <strong><em>mentally exhausting</em></strong> things I have ever had to do. <br><br>After the I submitted the daunting application, I kept wondering to myself, <strong>“how long will this take to be approved”</strong>, but no one at the SSA could answer this question for me. I was constantly told, “you will receive a letter in the mail after they review your application”<br><br>It took a while from what I remember, but I was denied (Like most first time applicants) and became extremely anxious when I learned that I only had 60 days to file my appeal. <br><br>I asked around in forums and searched the web for advice, but the most common advice I found was to “lawyer up” and put them in the driver’s seat. <br><br>…but that sounded expensive. <br><br>I already couldn’t afford my bills and I certainly didn’t think I could afford to pay for help.<br><br>But online, I read that disability attorneys and advocate groups are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved. <br><br>The attorney fees are capped at 25 percent and limited to a maximum of $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they only take on cases that they expect to win. <br><br>If they take a case and their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.<br><strong><br>This sounded too good to be true…</strong><br><br>And when researching advocacy groups that could help I found out that some shysters will charge you out of pocket for things like making copies of paperwork or postage for mailing documents.<br><br>I did know in my heart that hiring an attorney or advocacy group was the right move for me and my family. I just had to find one that didn\'t charge out of pocket fees as well...&nbsp;<br><br>I couldn’t afford to be stressed out and angry all the time at the SSA. <br><br>I needed to be there emotionally for my family. <br><br>I interviewed over 5 potential groups that I thought could help me and inquired about their success rates and if they charge any out of pocket fees. <br><br>I ended up using a service called the SS Claim Advocates, which was one of the best decisions I have made during this stressful process. <br><br>Even though I had to pay them a percentage of my back pay that was owed to me, I felt that they handled all of the headaches that I read about online and I was not charged any out of pocket fees. <br><br>There are a few other great options for advocacy groups out there that provide a similar service so <strong><em>I encourage you to do some research</em></strong>. <br><br>Although advocacy groups like <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">SS Claim Advocates</a> cannot guarantee a faster approval, they can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome. <br><br>I finally received approval 22 months after my initial application and my advice to those who are in a similar situation would be to research a reputable advocacy group and make sure to always ask if they charge any out of pocket expenses, because they might not mention that up front. <br><br>You are going to wait whether you go through it yourself or have an expert handle it for you, why not sleep in peace knowing someone is fighting for you and your family?<br><br>Or…<br><br>you can use the same service I used, click the link: <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">www.SSClaimAdvocates.com</a>. It’s pretty simple, just enter your information and describe your condition. <br><br>Someone will review your case and get back to you to discuss your options...whatever they may be.&nbsp;<br><br>Either way, I thought I would offer some consolation to those frustrated by the process. <br><br>Don’t waste your energy stressing over this process, do what my friend said and “lawyer up”, put them in the driver’s seat so you can be there for your family.</p></div>'),(4468,289,'tve_revision_tve_has_wistia_popover','0'),(4477,290,'tve_revision_tve_landing_page',''),(4478,290,'tve_revision_tve_content_before_more','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_heading\"><h1 data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\" style=\"text-align: left;\">The Best Decision I Made to Get Disability Benefits Approved...</h1></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">By John Sterling<br>Boston,MA<br><br>I thought it would never happen to me. Stunned by the words of my Doctor when he told me I would never be able to work again. At first I didn’t know how to take the news, I was only 52 years old, but quickly I became angry, anxious, and overwhelmed with racing thoughts. <br><br>How many of you reading this right now experienced the same emotions when you received the news? <br><br>I bet every one of you. <br><br>At first I felt alone and ashamed, then angry at life. Why did this happen to me? how am I going to make ends meet? What are my kids going to think about me as a parent? Or my wife, knowing she has to be the breadwinner? <br><br>I was draining my life savings and frequently chose to provide my family with food over paying my bills.<br><br>Then the debt collectors started to call, <strong><em>I NEEDED an income because my wife could not handle it all herself</em></strong>. <br><br>Through research, I learned that 375,000 Americans every year are retired by their doctors for disabilities. <br><br>I never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change my life. <br><br>The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of my wages have been paid into the Disability Insurance Trust Fund since I began working full time.<br><br>But you would think that a program you have been paying into your entire life would be easy to access in the event that you needed its resources, right? <br><br>Not…<br><br>Applying for Social Security Disability Insurance was one of the most <strong><em>mentally exhausting</em></strong> things I have ever had to do. <br><br>After the I submitted the daunting application, I kept wondering to myself, <strong>“how long will this take to be approved”</strong>, but no one at the SSA could answer this question for me. I was constantly told, “you will receive a letter in the mail after they review your application”<br><br>It took a while from what I remember, but I was denied (Like most first time applicants) and became extremely anxious when I learned that I only had 60 days to file my appeal. <br><br>I asked around in forums and searched the web for advice, but the most common advice I found was to “lawyer up” and put them in the driver’s seat. <br><br>…but that sounded expensive. <br><br>I already couldn’t afford my bills and I certainly didn’t think I could afford to pay for help.<br><br>But online, I read that disability attorneys and advocate groups are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved. <br><br>The attorney fees are capped at 25 percent and limited to a maximum of $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they only take on cases that they expect to win. <br><br>If they take a case and their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.<br><strong><br>This sounded too good to be true…</strong><br><br>And when researching advocacy groups that could help I found out that some shysters will charge you out of pocket for things like making copies of paperwork or postage for mailing documents.<br><br>I did know in my heart that hiring an attorney or advocacy group was the right move for me and my family. I just had to find one that didn\'t charge out of pocket fees as well...&nbsp;<br><br>I couldn’t afford to be stressed out and angry all the time at the SSA. <br><br>I needed to be there emotionally for my family. <br><br>I interviewed over 5 potential groups that I thought could help me and inquired about their success rates and if they charge any out of pocket fees. <br><br>I ended up using a service called the SS Claim Advocates, which was one of the best decisions I have made during this stressful process. <br><br>Even though I had to pay them a percentage of my back pay that was owed to me, I felt that they handled all of the headaches that I read about online and I was not charged any out of pocket fees. <br><br>There are a few other great options for advocacy groups out there that provide a similar service so <strong><em>I encourage you to do some research</em></strong>. <br><br>Although advocacy groups like <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">SS Claim Advocates</a> cannot guarantee a faster approval, they can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome. <br><br>I finally received approval 22 months after my initial application and my advice to those who are in a similar situation would be to research a reputable advocacy group and make sure to always ask if they charge any out of pocket expenses, because they might not mention that up front. <br><br>You are going to wait whether you go through it yourself or have an expert handle it for you, why not sleep in peace knowing someone is fighting for you and your family?<br><br>Or…<br><br>you can use the same service I used, click the link: <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">www.SSClaimAdvocates.com</a>. It’s pretty simple, just enter your information and describe your condition. <br><br>Someone will review your case and get back to you to discuss your options...whatever they may be.&nbsp;<br><br>Either way, I thought I would offer some consolation to those frustrated by the process. <br><br>Don’t waste your energy stressing over this process, do what my friend said and “lawyer up”, put them in the driver’s seat so you can be there for your family.</p></div>'),(4479,290,'tve_revision_tve_content_more_found',''),(4480,290,'tve_revision_tve_save_post',''),(4481,290,'tve_revision_tve_custom_css','@media (min-width: 300px){[data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\"] { line-height: 1.25em !important; }#tve_editor [data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\"] { font-size: 17px !important; font-family: Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif !important; }[data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\"] { line-height: 1.75em !important; }}'),(4482,290,'tve_revision_tve_user_custom_css',''),(4483,290,'tve_revision_tve_page_event