dn\'t charge out of pocket fees as well...&nbsp;<br><br>I couldn’t afford to be stressed out and angry all the time at the SSA. <br><br>I needed to be there emotionally for my family. <br><br>I interviewed over 5 potential groups that I thought could help me and inquired about their success rates and if they charge any out of pocket fees. <br><br>I ended up using a service called the SS Claim Advocates, which was one of the best decisions I have made during this stressful process. <br><br>Even though I had to pay them a percentage of my back pay that was owed to me, I felt that they handled all of the headaches that I read about online and I was not charged any out of pocket fees. <br><br>There are a few other great options for advocacy groups out there that provide a similar service so <strong><em>I encourage you to do some research</em></strong>. <br><br>Although advocacy groups like <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">SS Claim Advocates</a> cannot guarantee a faster approval, they can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome. <br><br>I finally received approval 22 months after my initial application and my advice to those who are in a similar situation would be to research a reputable advocacy group and make sure to always ask if they charge any out of pocket expenses, because they might not mention that up front. <br><br>You are going to wait whether you go through it yourself or have an expert handle it for you, why not sleep in peace knowing someone is fighting for you and your family?<br><br>Or…<br><br>you can use the same service I used, click the link: <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">www.SSClaimAdvocates.com</a>. It’s pretty simple, just enter your information and describe your condition. <br><br>Someone will review your case and get back to you to discuss your options...whatever they may be.&nbsp;<br><br>Either way, I thought I would offer some consolation to those frustrated by the process. <br><br>Don’t waste your energy stressing over this process, do what my friend said and “lawyer up”, put them in the driver’s seat so you can be there for your family.</p></div>'),(4491,290,'tve_revision_tve_has_wistia_popover','0'),(4492,63,'_thumbnail_id','111'),(4497,291,'tve_revision_tve_landing_page',''),(4498,291,'tve_revision_tve_content_before_more','<div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_heading\"><h1 data-css=\"tve-u-15f549bb8e3\" style=\"text-align: left;\">The Best Decision I Made to Get Disability Benefits Approved...</h1></div><div class=\"thrv_wrapper thrv_text_element tve_empty_dropzone\"><p data-css=\"tve-u-15f549113e5\">By John Sterling<br>Boston,MA<br><strong>Read Time: 3 minutes</strong><br><br>I thought it would never happen to me. Stunned by the words of my Doctor when he told me I would never be able to work again. At first I didn’t know how to take the news, I was only 52 years old, but quickly I became angry, anxious, and overwhelmed with racing thoughts. <br><br>How many of you reading this right now experienced the same emotions when you received the news? <br><br>I bet every one of you. <br><br>At first I felt alone and ashamed, then angry at life. Why did this happen to me? how am I going to make ends meet? What are my kids going to think about me as a parent? Or my wife, knowing she has to be the breadwinner? <br><br>I was draining my life savings and frequently chose to provide my family with food over paying my bills.<br><br>Then the debt collectors started to call, <strong><em>I NEEDED an income because my wife could not handle it all herself</em></strong>. <br><br>Through research, I learned that 375,000 Americans every year are retired by their doctors for disabilities. <br><br>I never planned for the abrupt brain aneurysm that would change my life. <br><br>The government, however, does plan, and a tiny percentage of my wages have been paid into the Disability 