 entire life would be easy to access in the event that you need it, right? Not…Applying for Social Security Disability Insurance was one of the most <strong><em>mentally exhausting</em></strong> things I have ever had to do. After the I submitted the daunting application, I kept wondering to myself, <strong>“how long will this take to be approved”</strong>, but no one at the SSA could answer this question for me. I was constantly told, “you will receive a notification after they review your application”It took a while from what I remember, but I was denied (Like most first time applicants) and became extremely anxious when I learned that I only had 60 days to file my appeal. I asked around in forums and searched the web for advice, but the most common advice I found was to “lawyer up” and put them in the driver’s seat. …but that sounded expensive. I already couldn’t afford my bills and I certainly didn’t think I could afford to pay for help.But online, I read that disability attorneys and advocate groups are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved. The attorney fees are capped at 25 percent and limited to a maximum of $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they only take on cases that they expect to win. If they take a case and their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.<strong>This sounded too good to be true…</strong>And when researching advocacy groups that could help I found out that some shysters will charge you out of pocket for things like making copies of paperwork or postage for mailing documents.I did know in my heart that hiring an attorney or advocacy group was the right move for me and my family. I just had to find one that didn\'t charge out of pocket fees as well...&nbsp;I couldn’t afford to be stressed out and angry all the time at the SSA. I needed to be there emotionally for my family. I interviewed over 5 potential groups that I thought could help me and inquired about their success rates and if they charge any out of pocket fees. I ended up using a service called the SS Claim Advocates, which was one of the best decisions I have made during this stressful process. Even though I had to pay them a percentage of my back pay that was owed to me, I felt that they handled all of the headaches that I read about online and I was not charged any out of pocket fees. There are a few other great options for advocacy groups out there that provide a similar service so <strong><em>I encourage you to do some research</em></strong>. Although advocacy groups like <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">SS Claim Advocates</a> cannot guarantee a faster approval, they can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome. I finally received approval 22 months after my initial application and my advice to those who are in a similar situation would be to research a reputable advocacy group and make sure to always ask if they charge any out of pocket expenses, because they might not mention that up front. You are going to wait whether you go through it yourself or have an expert handle it for you, why not sleep in peace knowing someone is fighting for you and your family?Or…you can use the same service I used, click the link: <a href=\"http://www.ssclaimadvocates.com\">www.SSClaimAdvocates.com</a>. It’s pretty simple, just enter your information and describe your condition. Someone will review your case and get back to you to discuss your options...whatever they may be.&nbsp;Either way, I thought I would offer some consolation to those frustrated by the process. Don’t waste your energy stressing over this process, do what my friend said and “lawyer up”, put them in the driver’s seat so you can be there for your family.</p>','The Best Decision I Made To Get My Disability Benefits Approved','','publish','open','open','','disability_approval','','','2017-11-17 14:50:10','2017-11-17 14:50:10','',0,'https://ssdinsider.com/?p=63',0,'post','',0),(64,1,'2017-10-25 17:19:25','2017-10-25 17:19:25','','DENIED! How Disabled Americans Are Using A Little Understood Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved!','','inherit','closed','closed','','63-revision-v1','','','2017-10-25 17:19:25','2017-10-25 17:19:25','',63,'https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/25/63-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(65,1,'2017-10-25 17:20:40','2017-10-25 17:20:40','','DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A Little Understood Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved!','','inherit','closed','closed','','63-revision-v1','','','2017-10-25 17:20:40','2017-10-25 17:20:40','',63,'https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/25/63-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(66,1,'2017-10-25 17:21:01','2017-10-25 17:21:01','','DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A Little Understood Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved','','inherit','closed','closed','','63-revision-v1','','','2017-10-25 17:21:01','2017-10-25 17:21:01','',63,'https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/25/63-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(67,1,'2017-10-25 17:32:26','2017-10-25 17:32:26','<p>October 27, 2017 Boston, MA:Americans who become disabled and need to apply for Social Security Disability benefits are stunned when they learn how difficult the U.S. Government makes it for them to gain approval.</p><p>John Sterling, a 56-year-old carpenter, became disabled in 2012. “When I got the news from my Doctor that I would not be able to work again, I was struck with a lot of anxiety” John recalls. “A lot of financial worries, but my first order of business was to apply for disability”.</p><p>He, like many Americans did not plan to become disabled, it happened suddenly, a brain aneurysm that he had no control over. “When I heard the news that I would not be able to work again, I thought it would be easy to apply for and gain approval for disability benefits that I have been paying into my entire life”, he said. “Boy was I wrong, the application was hard to complete and I received a letter of denial citing lack of hard medical evidence”.</p><p>This is not uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration shows that roughly 68% of first time applicants are initially denied. These denials are different case to case, but the most common reason is for failing to complete the application correctly and not supplying enough information.&nbsp;</p><p>Once a person is denied, they have 60 days to file an appeal. For people like John, this task can be overwhelming and personally deflating. He was puzzled, “I was crushed, how is it that I pay into a program for 25 years and then when I unfortunately need to use it, the Government is not there for me?”</p><p>&nbsp;It was time to try another option – A little understood resource that is available to every disabled American.That option, was reaching out to a disability advocacy firm to get some questions answered. “You should be able to just apply and get an approval from the Social Security Administration (SSA), but that’s just not the case. You can’t do it on your own anymore”.</p><p>Current statistics from the SSA estimate that the average wait time for a hearing is 602 days or 1.6 years. For people like John, receiving a denial because the application was not completed correctly might have added months onto the wait time for approval.</p><p>Every month of waiting drains even more from their savings account. “My bills were piling up and I could not sleep at night, constantly worrying about not being able to provide for my family, I did not want to screw up on the appeals” said John.</p><p>He finally gave into the ads he was seeing online for the disability advocacy group, <strong><em>Disability Freedom</em></strong>. “What ran through my mind were fears that using an attorney would cost too much and they would drain me even more, I just could not afford it.”</p><p>What many people are surprised to find out, is that disability attorneys and advocate groups, like the one John used, only get paid a small percentage of back disability payments after you win your approval. These payments are capped by law to 25% up to $6,000.00. This is one of the major reasons why advocacy groups are <em>extremely selective</em> in the cases they take on.</p><p>If a person never receives approval for disability benefits, they don’t have to pay a dime. “For me I didn’t mind paying someone after I won approval if it meant peace of mind.”, John said. “It was like I could finally sleep at night knowing that there was a group fighting for me, making sure everything was done correctly”.</p><p>Although disability advocacy groups cannot guarantee a quicker approval, they can reduce the time lost having to refile due to technical errors, which as mentioned above, is one of the major reasons for first time denials. “I’m happy with how everything turned out” said John. “If I was going through this process again, I would get on the phone with an advocacy group right away to see if they could help, it would have saved me months of unnecessary anxiety”.</p><p>To learn more about advocacy groups like the one mentioned in this article, <a href=\"https://www.disability-benefits-help.org/cpc/about-ssdi?utm_source=google&amp;utm_medium=cpc&amp;utm_term=disability%20benefits&amp;utm_content=225101598144&amp;utm_campaign=SSD+-+Phrase+Always&amp;__egma[MatchType]=p&amp;__egma[Network]=g&amp;__egma[Device]=c&amp;__egma[Creative]=225101598144&amp;__egma[Placement]=&amp;__egma[AdPosition]=1t1&amp;gclid=EAIaIQobChMI-_2d2KaM1wIVF7jACh0fsQS1EAAYASAAEgId3_D_BwE\"><u>click here</u></a></p>','DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A Little Understood Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved','','inherit','closed','closed','','63-revision-v1','','','2017-10-25 17:32:26','2017-10-25 17:32:26','',63,'https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/25/63-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(68,1,'2017-10-25 17:32:26','2017-10-25 17:32:26','<p>October 27, 2017 Boston, MA:Americans who become disabled and need to apply for Social Security Disability benefits are stunned when they learn how difficult the U.S. Government makes it for them to gain approval.</p><p>John Sterling, a 56-year-old carpenter, became disabled in 2012. “When I got the news from my Doctor that I would not be able to work again, I was struck with a lot of anxiety” John recalls. “A lot of financial worries, but my first order of business was to apply for disability”.</p><p>He, like many Americans did not plan to become disabled, it happened suddenly, a brain aneurysm that he had no control over. “When I heard the news that I would not be able to work again, I thought it would be easy to apply for and gain approval for disability benefits that I have been paying into my entire life”, he said. “Boy was I wrong, the application was hard to complete and I received a letter of denial citing lack of hard medical evidence”.</p><p>This is not uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration shows that roughly 68% of first time applicants are initially denied. These denials are different case to case, but the most common reason is for failing to complete the application correctly and not supplying enough information.&nbsp;</p><p>Once a person is denied, they have 60 days to file an appeal. For people like John, this task can be overwhelming and personally deflating. He was puzzled, “I was crushed, how is it that I pay into a program for 25 years and then when I unfortunately need to use it, the Government is not there for me?”</p><p>&nbsp;It was time to try another option – A little understood resource that is available to every disabled American.That option, was reaching out to a disability advocacy firm to get some questions answered. “You should be abl