 not want to screw up on the appeals” said John.</p><p>He finally gave into the ads he was seeing online for the disability advocacy group, <strong><em>Disability Freedom</em></strong>. “What ran through my mind were fears that using an attorney would cost too much and they would drain me even more, I just could not afford it.”</p><p>What many people are surprised to find out, is that disability attorneys and advocate groups, like the one John used, only get paid a small percentage of back disability payments after you win your approval. These payments are capped by law to 25% up to $6,000.00. This is one of the major reasons why advocacy groups are <em>extremely selective</em> in the cases they take on.</p><p>If a person never receives approval for disability benefits, they don’t have to pay a dime. “For me I didn’t mind paying someone after I won approval if it meant peace of mind.”, John said. “It was like I could finally sleep at night knowing that there was a group fighting for me, making sure everything was done correctly”.</p><p>Although disability advocacy groups cannot guarantee a quicker approval, they can reduce the time lost having to refile due to technical errors, which as mentioned above, is one of the major reasons for first time denials. “I’m happy with how everything turned out” said John. “If I was going through this process again, I would get on the phone with an advocacy group right away to see if they could help, it would have saved me months of unnecessary anxiety”.</p><p>To learn more about advocacy groups like the one mentioned in this article, <a href=\"https://www.disability-benefits-help.org/cpc/about-ssdi?utm_source=google&amp;utm_medium=cpc&amp;utm_term=disability%20benefits&amp;utm_content=225101598144&amp;utm_campaign=SSD+-+Phrase+Always&amp;__egma[MatchType]=p&amp;__egma[Network]=g&amp;__egma[Device]=c&amp;__egma[Creative]=225101598144&amp;__egma[Placement]=&amp;__egma[AdPosition]=1t1&amp;gclid=EAIaIQobChMI-_2d2KaM1wIVF7jACh0fsQS1EAAYASAAEgId3_D_BwE\"><u>click here</u></a></p>','DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A Little Understood Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved','','inherit','closed','closed','','63-revision-v1','','','2017-10-25 17:37:13','2017-10-25 17:37:13','',63,'https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/25/63-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(71,1,'2017-10-25 17:37:36','2017-10-25 17:37:36','','DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A Little Understood Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved','','inherit','closed','closed','','63-revision-v1','','','2017-10-25 17:37:36','2017-10-25 17:37:36','',63,'https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/25/63-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2017-10-25 17:39:19','2017-10-25 17:39:19','<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\">DENIED! How 428,654 Disabled Americans Are Using A <em>Little Understood</em> Resource To Finally Get Their Disability Benefits Approved.</h1><p>October 27, 2017 Boston, MA:Americans who become disabled and need to apply for Social Security Disability benefits are stunned when they learn how difficult the U.S. Government makes it for them to gain approval.</p><p>John Sterling, a 56-year-old carpenter, became disabled in 2012. “When I got the news from my Doctor that I would not be able to work again, I was struck with a lot of anxiety” John recalls. “A lot of financial worries, but my first order of business was to apply for disability”.</p><p>He, like many Americans did not plan to become disabled, it happened suddenly, a brain aneurysm that he had no control over. “When I heard the news that I would not be able to work again, I thought it would be easy to apply for and gain approval for disability benefits that I have been paying into my entire life”, he said. “Boy was I wrong, the application was hard to complete and I received a letter of denial citing lack of hard medical evidence”.</p><p>This is not uncommon. Data collected from the Social Security Administration shows that rou