understand why the government wasn’t willing to help me.”</strong></em></h4><p>Current data from the SSA estimates wait times for appeal hearings to take over 600 days, or nearly 20 months.&nbsp;</p><p>Every month of waiting was another month that Sterling was pulling from his life’s reserves to cover daily expenses, slowly draining his savings account. “I wasn’t sleeping, I was constantly worrying,” Sterling said.&nbsp;</p><p>“I was the breadwinner, and I needed to be able to provide for my family. It killed me that I wasn’t able to do that.”In need of another option, Sterling turned online for legal advice. “A friend recommended I look for an advocacy group, but that sounded expensive. I already couldn’t afford my bills,” he said. “I certainly didn’t think I could afford help.”</p><p>But online, he learned that disability attorneys and advocate groups such as Disability United are paid only a small percentage of back disability payments, and only after a client’s application is approved.</p><p>These payments are capped at 25 percent and limited to $6,000 by law. For this reason, many advocacy groups are extremely selective about their clients, and they take cases that they expect to win. If their client is never approved for disability benefits, the client doesn’t pay a dime.</p><p>And though disability advocacy does not guarantee a faster approval process, professional groups like these can vastly reduce the time lost due to technical errors and refiling—one of the top reasons for first-time denials—and greatly improve the chances of a favorable outcome.</p><p>Sterling said he didn’t mind paying after the approval for the immense peace of mind he gained. “Knowing that I had a group of experts fighting for my case meant that I could finally sleep at night.</p><p>I gave myself the best chance of a good outcome.”The best outcome was what Sterling, and the many other disability applicants every year who seek out help, received. Advocacy groups and disability attorneys build sophisticated cases for their clients to ensure that applications make it through all the hoops, and in today’s complex system, it truly takes an expert.</p><p>“You can’t do it on your own these days,” Sterling said. “My advocacy group gave me so much help and reassurance. I could have saved myself months of unnecessary anxiety if I had just known that sooner.”</p><p>If you want to learn more about advocacy groups like Disability United to see if they can help you or a loved one, click here.</p>','Is This The Fastest Way To Get Disability Benefits Approved After A Denial?','','inherit','closed','closed','','77-revision-v1','','','2017-10-30 17:57:07','2017-10-30 17:57:07','',77,'https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/30/77-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(84,3,'2017-10-31 14:20:35','2017-10-31 14:20:35','<a href=\"https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/31/how-to-plan-for-the-unforeseen/\"><span></span></a><span style=\"font-size: 38px;line-height: 47px;\"><a href=\"https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/31/how-to-plan-for-the-unforeseen/\">How to Plan for the Unforeseen</a></span>Even thinking about an unexpected, life-changing event can be unsettling. But death or illness can happen at any time. Unfortunately,&#91;...&#93;<a href=\"https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/31/how-to-plan-for-the-unforeseen/\">Read More</a>&nbsp;<span></span><a href=\"https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/31/congress-tries-to-squeeze-more-out-of-social-security-wrecking-its-customer-service/\"><span></span></a><span style=\"font-size: 22px;line-height: 21px;\"><a href=\"https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/31/congress-tries-to-squeeze-more-out-of-social-security-wrecking-its-customer-service/\">Congress tries to squeeze more out of Social Security, wrecking its customer service</a></span><a href=\"https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/31/congress-tries-to-squeeze-more-out-of-social-security-wrecking-its-customer-service/\">Read More</a>&nbsp;<span></span><a href=\"https://ssdinsider.com/2017/10/31/174/\"><span></span></a><span 